record_data.record_title: Terms and Conditions
record_data.record_plain_text:
TERMS AND CONDITIONS OF MISSISSIPPI POWER COMPANY FOR THE PURCHASE OF ELECTRIC SERVICE FOR RESALE BY WHOLESALE CUSTOMERS
DELIVERY POINTS
1. Wholesale electric service for resale pursuant to this tariff contemplates the rendering of such service at one or more delivery points. A "Service Delivery Point Contract" will be executed by Company and Customer for each such delivery point, said contract form being a component of this tariff. This kind of service at each delivery point shall be in the form of three phase alternating current, of approximately sixty hertz and at the pressure and quantity as provided in such contracts.
2. Should establishment of an additional delivery point from Company's 115 kV system involve construction by Company of a stepdown transformer substation, the contracted capacity for such delivery point shall not be less than 5,000 kilowatts. Should establishment of an additional delivery point involve a transmission line extension by Company to a location in an area not embraced within Company's service area as certificated by Mississippi Public Service Commission, Customer shall pay Company, in addition to all other charges, an amount equal to Company's reasonable cost of owning and maintaining the entire length of such extensions and associated right of way so long as such extension is maintained solely for such use by Customer. Should Customer construct transmission line extensions from a delivery point, Company, as a condition precedent to establishment of service hereunder, may require Customer to provide such switching and protective equipment as may be necessary to protect Company's transmission system. Company shall make all connections of its system to Customer's system.
METERING EQUIPMENT AND TESTS
3. The electric service supplied at each delivery point will be measured by commercially acceptable metering equipment, installed, owned and maintained by Company. If requested by Company, Customer will provide a suitable location for such metering equipment.
4. Company's metering equipment installed at each delivery point for billing purposes shall, by comparison with accurate standards, be tested and calibrated by Company at statistically appropriate intervals, not to exceed twenty-four (24) months. The expense of such meter test shall be borne by Company. Company will notify Customer in advance of any meter test hereunder so that Customer's representative may be present. If a meter shall be found incorrect or inaccurate, it shall be restored to an accurate condition or a new meter shall be substituted.
Customer shall have the right to request that a special meter test be made at any time. If any test made at Customer's request discloses that the meter tested is registering within two percent (2%) of normal, Customer shall bear the expense of such test.
The results of all such tests and calibrations shall be open to examination by Customer and a report of every test shall be furnished immediately to Customer. Any meter tested and found to be not more than two percent (2%) above or below shall be considered to be registering correctly. If as a result of any test any meter is found to register in excess of two percent (2%) either above or below normal, then the readings of such meters previously used for billing purposes shall be adjusted according to the percentage of inaccuracy so found; but no such adjustment shall extend beyond ninety (90) days previous to the date of such test.
For any period that meters are found to have failed to register, it shall be assumed that the kilowatts and kilowatt hours of electric service delivered during such period are the same as that for a period of like service, such period to be agreed to by Customer and Company.
BILLING AND PAYMENTS
5. Meters shall be regularly read by the Company at intervals of approximately thirty (30) days as agreed by the parties. Bills for electric service furnished to Customer at each delivery point shall be rendered by Company to Customer monthly, and shall be payable at the office of Company designated on each bill within fifteen (15) days after the bill therefor shall have been mailed to Customer. If such due date falls on a Sunday or holiday, the bill shall be due on the next day following such Sunday or holiday.
For failure of Customer to pay any bill accruing under this contract on or before the fifteenth day after the due date of such bill, Company may discontinue the supply of electric service, provided at least fifteen (15) days written notice has been given of such intention to discontinue the service. Customer may avoid such discontinuance by paying such bill before the expiration of the above fifteen (15) day notice; provided however, in the event Customer disputes in writing the correctness of such bill prior to the expiration of the fifteen (15) day notice period, Customer may, in such event, prevent discontinuance of service hereunder by depositing with the Company the amount of the bill so disputed, such deposit to be subject to the right of Customer to receive, either by way of refund or credit on a subsequent bill, the amount by which the deposit is determined to exceed the correct amount due.
ELECTRIC SYSTEMS
6. All of the electric lines and equipment located on Customer's side of the point of service delivery hereunder, except Company's metering equipment, shall be furnished and maintained by Customer.
Both parties hereto agree to exercise reasonable care to construct and maintain their respective electric systems, insofar as each other party is concerned, in accordance with specifications at least equal to those prescribed by the Mississippi Public Service Commission and/or the National Electrical Safety Code, to maintain their systems at all times in a reasonably safe operating condition, and to maintain their systems in such manner and condition as not unreasonably to interfere with the service of each of these contracting parties to its, respective customers.
Customer agrees that electric energy hereunder will be distributed in such a manner that the requirements at each point of service delivery from Company will be reasonably balanced between phases.
Customer agrees that the portion of the electric distribution system of Customer supplied with electric energy from each delivery point will normally be operated separately from the portions which are supplied with electric energy from other delivery points or from sources other than Company, but may, from time to time as operating conditions warrant and if there is adequate capacity in Company's facilities, switch loads from delivery point to delivery point, in which case an appropriate adjustment will be made to Customers' monthly kilowatt requirement for each delivery point to prevent duplicate billing of demand charges.
Should the voltage at the point of delivery for any delivery point vary more than five percent (5%) from Company's normal operating voltage at such location, as specified by Company from time to time, it will notify Customer so that Customer may, should it so desire, change the tap settings of its transformers for the receipt of electric service.
Customer shall not, without the written permission of Company, add load to a service delivery point which shall impose on Company's system excessive voltage flicker or harmonic distortion.
RIGHT OF ACCESS
7. Each party will give all necessary permission to each other to enable the agents of the other party to perform the obligations of the parties, and will give each other the right by their duly authorized agents and employees to enter the premises of the other at a reasonable times for the purposes of reading or checking meters; for inspecting, testing, repairing, renewing or exchanging any or all of its equipment which may be located on the premises of the other; or for performing any other work incident to rendering the service provided for hereunder.
CONTINUITY OF SERVICE
8. In the event that Company is delayed in the delivery of electric service at any delivery point contracted for by strike, riot, invasion, fire, flood, explosion, breakdown, act of God or the public enemy, or any cause beyond its control, the time fixed for the commencement of delivery of electric service at such delivery point shall be correspondingly extended. Company shall not be liable to Customer nor shall Customer be liable to Company, by reason of failure of Company to deliver, or Customer to receive electric service as the result of fire, strike, riot, explosion, flood, accident, breakdown, acts of God or the public enemy, or other acts beyond the control of the party affected, it being the intention of each party to relieve the other of the obligation to supply electric service or to receive and pay for such service when, as a result of any of the above mentioned causes, either party may be unable to deliver or use in whole or in part the electric service contracted to be delivered or received. Both parties shall be prompt and diligent in removing and overcoming the cause or causes of such interruptions, but nothing herein shall be construed as permitting Company to refuse to deliver, or Customer to refuse to receive electric service after the cause of an interruption has been removed. Company agrees that, in the event of an interruption of electric service to Customer, it will, without discrimination between the ultimate retail loads of Customer and Company, make every effort to restore service to Customer concurrently with restoration of service to its other customers, except for reasons of sound utility operating practice.
9. Company does not guarantee that the supply of electric service hereunder will be free from interruptions; and it is agreed that interruptions of the Company's service, occasioned by any of the causes mentioned in the foregoing paragraph, shall not constitute a breach of this contract on the part of Company, and Company shall not be liable to Customer for damages resulting therefrom. In the event of an interruption to service, Company will restore the service as soon as it can reasonably do so and will at all times exert itself toward the end of supplying as nearly constant service as is reasonably practicable. In case of impaired or defective service, Customer shall immediately give notice to the nearest office of Company by telephone.
LIABILITY FOR DAMAGE
10. The electric energy supplied under the contract between the parties is supplied upon the express condition that, after it passes the point of service delivery of each delivery point, it becomes the property of Customer; and Company shall not be liable for loss or damage to any person or property whatsoever resulting directly or indirectly from the use, misuse, or presence of the said electric energy on Customer's premises, or elsewhere, after it passes the point of delivery to Customer, except where such loss or damage shall be shown to have been occasioned by negligence of Company, its agents or employees. Each party hereto agrees to indemnify and save harmless the other from payment of any sum or sums of money to any person whatsoever, including attorneys' fees and court costs, which such party may be called upon to pay on account of damages to property or personal injuries to individuals, whether or not resulting in death, resulting from or which may be in any way caused by the negligence of such party in the maintenance, construction or operation of its lines, apparatus, appliances, or other equipment; provided, however, such indemnity shall not apply in favor of either party when and if such damages or injuries shall have been occasioned solely by the negligence of such party or its employees.
RATE CHANGES
11. Company reserves the right to change, in the manner prescribed by law, the rate schedule and Terms and Conditions components of its tariff. Likewise, Customer reserves the right to oppose any changes sought by the Company, and to seek changes in the manner prescribed by law to the rate schedule and Terms and Conditions components of the Company's tariff. Should any change be lawfully made in said components, from and after the effective date of such change, service shall be subject to and in accordance therewith.

AMENDED AND RESTATED
SHARED SERVICE AGREEMENT
This Amended and Restated Shared Service Agreement (the "Agreement") is made effective the 26 day of May, 2022 (the "Effective Date"), by and between Cooperative Energy, a Mississippi electric cooperative, f/k/a South Mississippi Electric Power Association ("Customer") and Mississippi Power Company, a Mississippi corporation ("MPC") (individually "Party" or collectively "Parties"), for the modification of service responsibility for certain Customer delivery points on or near the MPC transmission system.
WHEREAS, currently, Customer and MPC are parties to that certain Shared Services Agreement, dated September 18, 2017, filed with and accepted by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("FERC") in Docket No. ER18-30-000 and made effective as of December 4, 2017 ("Current Shared Services Agreement"). The Current Shared Services Agreement originally allowed Customer to take over the service of up to thirty-six percent (36%) (currently thirty-three and sixth-tenths percent (33.6%) due to Converted Delivery Points) in up to two and sixth-tenths percent (2.6%) annual increments of Customer's Members' load requirements at Shared Service Delivery Points with MPC continuing to provide the remaining delivery point service requirements under the MRA Tariff. Moreover, under the Current Shared Services Agreement, Customer has the right to convert existing delivery points; however, under the Current Shared Services Agreement, these Converted Delivery Points count against the yearly incremental percent increase as well as the thirty-six percent (36%) cumulative cap value.
WHEREAS, under the Current Shared Services Agreement, the Parties provide Requirements Service for their respective portion of Shared Service to Customer delivery points under MPC's MRA Tariff and MPC provides network transmission service to those Shared Service Delivery Points under the Southern Companies OATT.
WHEREAS, the Parties desire to amend and restate the Current Shared Services Agreement in its entirety to, among other things, provide for an equitable and orderly transition of load service at the Shared Service Delivery Points, so that Customer will provide one hundred percent (100%) of its Members' load requirements at those delivery points effective January 1, 2036. Starting in 2022, Customer would automatically start increasing the Customer Shared Service Load Percentage in annual increments of two and one-half percent (2.5%) through 2035. Starting in 2036, Customer will serve one hundred percent (100%) of its Members' load requirements in the MPC transmission area. MPC will have the obligation to serve its load ratio share of the remaining Shared Service Delivery Points' service requirements until Customer takes one hundred percent (100%) of the load service requirements, but in any event, such obligation will terminate on January 1, 2036. In addition, Customer will have the option to convert existing Shared Service Delivery Points and their corresponding load to the Customer's transmission system without any impacts to the yearly incremental increase. WHEREAS, this Agreement, on the terms and subject to the conditions set forth herein, shall amend, replace, and restate, in its entirety, the Current Shared Services Agreement to the aforementioned purposes. NOW, THEREFORE, for and in consideration of the mutual agreements herein, the Parties intending to be bound, do hereby agree as follows: Article 1: Definitions: The following definitions shall apply to this Agreement, unless otherwise indicated: "Automatic Annual Load Percentage Increase" means the automatic annual increase of Customer's Shared Service Load Percentage effective January 1st for each calendar year of the Term, equal to two and one-half percent (2.5%), unless Customer provides written notification to MPC, by November 1st of prior year, of Customer's decision to increase Customer's Shared Service Load Percentage by less than two and one-half percent (2.5%) for any subsequent year of the Term. The Automatic Annual Load Percentage Increase shall commence on January 1st of the calendar year immediately following the Service Modification Date. "Agreement" shall have the meaning set forth in the Preamble. "Converted Delivery Points or CDP" are Shared Service Delivery Points that Customer elects in accordance with the provisions of this Agreement to convert from Shared Service under the MRA Tariff to exclusive Requirements Service by Customer and shall be directly connected to and served exclusively by Customer's transmission system. "Convertible Delivery Point Option" shall have the meaning set forth in Article 6. "Current Shared Services Agreement" shall have the meaning set forth in the first WHEREAS clause. "Customer" shall have the meaning set forth in the Preamble. "Customer Shared Service Load Percentage" means the percentage of Shared Service load for which the Customer shall provide Requirements Service as defined in Article 3. "Customer Transfer Date" shall mean the Operating Time of midnight on January 1, 2036. "Day" means a calendar day; provided, however, for the purposes of this Agreement, a Day shall begin and end at the applicable Operating Time. "Effective Date" shall have the meaning set forth in the Preamble. "Interconnection Facilities" shall mean the physical facilities, improvements and equipment which must be made or installed at or to MPC's existing transmission system to accommodate the interconnection of Customer's transmission line to New Delivery Points. "Member(s)" means the entities with ownership interests in Customer that are current MRA Tariff customers, as listed in Exhibit A. "MPC" shall have the meaning set forth in the Preamble. "MPC Shared Service Load Percentage" means the percentage of Shared Service load for which MPC shall provide Requirements Service as defined in Article 3. "MRA Tariff" means MPC's Federal Energy Regulatory Commission's Wholesale Tariff Volume No. 1 for cost-based service, as the tariff may be amended. "New Delivery Point" shall have the meaning set forth in Article 4. "NITSA" shall have the meaning set forth in Article 11. "OATT" means Southern Operating Companies Open Access Transmission Tariff, FERC Electric Tariff Fourth Revised Volume No. 5, as the tariff may be amended. "Operating Committee" shall have the meaning set forth in Article 9. "Operating Procedures" shall have the meaning set forth in Article 9. "Operating Representatives" shall have the meaning set forth in Article 9. "Operating Time" means the time standard used to dispatch, schedule, and control generation by the Southern Companies. At the time of the Effective Date, Operating Time is Central Prevailing Time. "Party" and "Parties" shall have the meaning set forth in the Preamble. "Requirements Service" includes, but is not limited to, the responsibility to provide capacity and energy requirements, real-time load following, reserves and planning requirements. "SEPA" refers to the Southeastern Power Administration, an agency of the Department of Energy. "SEPA Energy and Capacity" refers to the energy and capacity MPC receives from SEPA and delivers to certain of Customer's Members pursuant to the Agreement dated September 30, 1996, by and between MPC and SEPA. "Service Modification Date" means the effective date of service modifications provided for in this Agreement, as accepted or otherwise set by FERC. "Shared Service" means the Parties' respective obligations to provide Requirements Service to the Shared Service Delivery Points in the relative amounts of Customer Shared Service Load Percentage and MPC Shared Service Load Percentage pursuant to this Agreement. "Shared Service Delivery Points" means those delivery points for which the Parties shall have Shared Service responsibilities pursuant to the provisions of this Agreement and the MRA Tariff. These delivery points, unless modified under Article 6, are listed in Exhibit A. "Single Customer Delivery Point" means a Customer Delivery Point that exclusively serves a single retail customer as specified in Article 7. "Term" shall have the meaning set forth in Article 2.
Article 2: Service Modification Date & Term of Agreement
1. The term of this Agreement shall begin on the Effective Date and shall remain in effect until 12:00 a.m. Operating Time on January 1, 2036 to coincide with the Customer Transfer Date ("Term"). This Agreement will replace only the ten (10) year termination notice between MPC and Cooperative Energy as provided under the MRA Tariff. Neither Party may terminate this Agreement prior to the expiration of the Term. 2. Prior to the Service Modification Date, MPC agrees to seek regulatory approval for a modification to the MRA Tariff and any other modifications, agreements, or other filings necessary to allow up to one hundred percent (100%) of Shared Service load to be served by Customer effective January 1, 2036, consistent with the terms of this Agreement. 3. MPC shall request an effective date for the service modifications described in this Agreement for the day after the date of filing this Agreement with FERC, however, the Parties acknowledge FERC may accept that effective date or set an alternative effective date. Customer shall cooperate and support MPC in its efforts to obtain regulatory approval of the service modifications described in this Agreement. 4. The service modifications described in this Agreement shall not be effective until the Service Modification Date. 5. In the event that FERC does not approve this Agreement as presented, either Party shall have the right to issue the 10 year termination notice as described in the MRA Tariff, and said notice shall be deemed to have been issued on January 1, 2022.
Article 3: Service Changes 1. Commencing on the Service Modification Date, all Shared Service Delivery Points shall be subject to the terms of this Amended and Restated Shared Services Agreement as provided herein. 2. On and after the Service Modification Date (i) Customer shall supply a portion of Requirements Service to all Shared Service Delivery Points equal to the Customer Shared Service Load Percentage, and (ii) MPC shall supply a portion of the Requirements Service to all Shared Service Delivery Points equal to the MPC Shared Service Load Percentage. 3. The initial Customer Shared Service Load Percentage and MPC Shared Service Load Percentage shall be calculated in accordance with the respective load responsibility of the Parties as of December 31, 2021, as set forth in Exhibit A. 4. The MPC Shared Service Load Percentage shall at all-times during the Term of the Agreement equal one hundred percent (100%) minus the Customer Shared Service Load Percentage. 5. Customer Shared Service Load Percentage each year of the Term shall be the Customer Shared Service Load Percentage from the previous year, plus the Automatic Annual Load Percentage Increase for the subject year. In the initial year, the initial Customer Shared Service Load Percentage, as provided in Item 3 of this Article 3 shall be the starting point for such calculation. The calculation shall be jointly prepared, reviewed, and approved each year by the Operating Committee. 6. Subject to any amendment to or modification of MPC's agreement with SEPA, SEPA Energy and Capacity shall continue to be treated in a similar manner under this Agreement as it was previously treated under the MRA Tariff and the Current Shared Services Agreement prior to the Service Modification Date, and whereas previously, the amount of SEPA Energy and Capacity delivered to the designated MRA delivery points was deducted from the designated delivery points' MPC's billed energy and capacity sales to Customer under the MRA Tariff; under this Agreement, in lieu of individual delivery point credits, MPC shall give Customer a credit on the next available monthly MRA Tariff invoice an amount equal to the total dollar value of credits of SEPA Energy and Capacity under the MRA Tariff; provided however, that in no event shall SEPA kW and kWh credit to Customer exceed MPC's Shared Services load. The Parties further agree to work with each other and SEPA to modify or terminate, as applicable, the current agreement between SEPA and MPC in advance of the Customer Transfer Date, to provide for an orderly transition of the substance of the SEPA arrangement to an agreement between Customer and SEPA.
Article 4: New Delivery Points 1. Customer shall have the right to establish any new Shared Service Delivery Points after the Service Modification Date (each a "New Delivery Point") on the MPC transmission system (other than Single Customer Delivery Points which shall be treated in accordance with Article 7 below). 2. Such delivery points shall be served as a Shared Service Delivery Point and shall be added to Exhibit A by the Operating Committee. 3. Customer shall give MPC a minimum of twelve (12) month notice of the addition of any New Delivery Point that shall be served as a Shared Service Delivery Point under this Agreement. 4. Consistent with the current process for new MRA delivery points, MPC shall design, construct, own, and maintain Interconnection Facilities for New Delivery Points. To avoid any double payment for transmission services and for consistency between the MRA Tariff and OATT tariffs, MPC shall reimburse Customer the amounts directly assigned to Customer pursuant to the OATT for the costs of the design, construction, ownership, and maintenance of Interconnection Facilities for the New Delivery Points, and those charges will be directly assigned to and recovered through the MRA Tariff; provided, however, that the ownership of and capital costs, including contributions in aid of construction, associated with the design, construction, ownership, and maintenance of Interconnection Facilities for New Delivery Points established after the Service Modification Date shall be jointly evaluated by MPC and Customer on a case-by-case basis and any such Interconnection Facilities determined to be owned by MPC shall be billed to and recovered from Customer prior to MPC's commencement of construction of such Interconnection Facilities. Article 5: Automatic Annual Customer Load Increase Following the Service Modification Date, each year the Customer Shared Service Load Percentage shall increase by the Automatic Annual Load Percentage Increase. The effective date of each increase shall be January 1st of each year during the Term of this Agreement. In the event FERC approval is delayed, the automatic annual customer load increase will continue at 2.5% per year until FERC's final ruling. Article 6: Convertible Delivery Point Option 1. Customer shall have the right and option, but not the obligation, to convert a Shared Service Delivery Point to a Converted Delivery Point under this Agreement. Any conversion shall only be effective at a specific Operating Time, agreed upon by the parties (typically January 1st of each year) following notice provided by Customer as required under Paragraph 2 below. Upon conversion of a Shared Service Delivery Point, Customer shall provide full Requirements Service to such delivery point and such delivery point shall be directly connected to and served exclusively from Customer's transmission system (a "Convertible Delivery Point Option"). 2. Subject to Paragraph 4 below, to exercise the Convertible Delivery Point Option for a particular year, Customer shall provide written notice to MPC no less than one hundred eighty (180) days prior to the date on which the conversion is to occur. 3. The conversion of a Shared Service Delivery Point shall be in its entirety, partial conversion is prohibited. 4. The conversion of a Shared Service Delivery Point to a Converted Delivery Point shall not adjust or have any effect on the Automatic Annual Load Percentage Increase in the Customer Shared Service Load Percentage for the non-converted delivery points, MPC Shared Service Load Percentage, or the Automatic Annual Load Percentage Increase as a result of any Converted Delivery Points. For the avoidance of doubt, it is the Parties' intent that the percentages of load served by each Party hereto at each non-converted MRA delivery point as of the Service Modification Date shall be automatically adjusted pursuant to Article 5 each year of the Agreement without regard to the cumulative total kWhs served for all delivery points, and without regard to any load served exclusively by Customer at any Converted Delivery Points. 5. Once a Shared Service Delivery Point has been converted pursuant to this Article 6, such delivery point shall no longer be subject to Shared Service under this Agreement and shall no longer be considered part of Shared Services load. Such delivery point will be removed from Exhibit A and an updated Exhibit A shall be issued; provided, however, removals of delivery points shall not be deemed an amendment to this agreement requiring compliance with Article 13, Paragraph 5. Article 7: Single Customer Delivery Points New and existing Single Customer Delivery Points shall be specifically excluded from the terms of the Agreement, unless otherwise agreed to by the Parties. Customer shall have no obligation to take Requirements Service, and MPC shall have no obligation to supply Requirements Service, for such Single Customer Delivery Points under the MRA tariff. Article 8: Delivery Point Retirements
Customer may retire a Shared Service Delivery Point if Customer determines that the delivery point is no longer needed for reliability reasons. If a Shared Service Delivery Point is retired, all load associated with retired delivery points shall either be transferred to other Shared Service Delivery Points or, if not so transferred, be deemed an exercise of the Convertible Delivery Point Option of Article 6 and subject to the provisions therein. Article 9: Operating Procedure/Operating Committee 1. Customer and MPC shall each designate one representative and one alternate ("Operating Representatives") who shall act for the respective Parties in matters pertaining to detailed operating arrangements for service hereunder. The Operating Representatives shall comprise and be referred to as the Operating Committee. Evidence of such appointment shall be given by notice to each of the Parties in writing, and such appointments may be changed at any time by similar notice. 2. The Operating Committee shall have responsibility for the following: a. establishment of arrangements for metering, telemetering, telecommunications, data acquisition, and other activities associated with the delivery and receipt of energy hereunder to the extent not provided for by this Agreement or the applicable transmission service arrangements; b. communications regarding methods and procedures for accounting and billing hereunder; c. establishment of Operating Procedures; and d. such other duties as may be conferred upon it by mutual agreement of Customer and MPC. 3. Both Customer and MPC shall cooperate in providing the Operating Committee all information required in the performance of its duties. If the Operating Committee is unable to agree on any matter falling under its jurisdiction, such matters shall be referred by the Operating Representatives to their principals for a decision. Failure of the principals to agree on any matter referred to them shall not constitute a basis for termination of this Agreement, but such disagreement shall be subject to review by FERC. All decisions or agreements made by the Operating Committee shall be evidenced in writing. 4. Unless otherwise agreed, the Operating Committee shall hold an annual meeting at a mutually convenient time and place to review the duties set forth herein. When requested by either Customer or MPC, the Operating Committee shall also meet at the earliest opportunity for consideration of matters under its jurisdiction. 5. The Parties have previously established the protocol under which the Parties shall perform their respective responsibilities under this Agreement ("Operating Procedures"), including: a. method of day-to-day communication; b. key personnel lists; c. sharing of load forecasts; d. calculation of the Customer Shared Service Load Percentage; e. item 2.a. and 2.b. of this Article; and f. such other matters as the Operating Representatives shall agree are appropriate. The Operating Representatives shall be responsible for modifying, from time to time, the Operating Procedures in writing to reflect agreed changes, and the Parties agree to review and modify, if applicable, the Operating Procedures for the implementation of the terms of this Agreement within ninety (90) days following the Effective Date, to be effective upon, or as close thereto, the Service Modification Date. 6. In no event shall any Operating Procedures under this Agreement modify (or be construed as modifying) any of the terms and conditions of this Agreement or the MRA Tariff. In the event of a conflict or inconsistency between this Agreement, the MRA Tariff, and any Operating Procedures, the terms of this Agreement and the MRA Tariff shall govern to the extent of the conflict or inconsistency. If the terms of the Agreement and the MRA Tariff are inconsistent, the Agreement shall govern to the extent of the conflict or inconsistency.
Article 10: Customer Transfer Date
On the Customer Transfer Date, all load service remaining at the Shared Service Delivery Points shall be equitably and orderly transitioned so that Customer shall provide one hundred percent (100%) of its Members' load requirements at those delivery points.
Article 11: Transmission Service, Billing and Credit
1. Customer shall contract, take and pay for Network Integrated Transmission Service ("NITSA") for all loads on its Shared Service Delivery Points under Southern Companies' OATT. 2. MPC shall give Customer a credit on the next available monthly MRA Tariff invoice in an amount equal to Customer's NITSA payments for transmission and required ancillary service for the portion of Shared Service load not served by the Customer, which shall include the portion served under the MRA Tariff and the Customer's contribution of SEPA Energy and Capacity; provided however, that in no event shall SEPA kw and kWh credit to Customer exceed MPC's Shared Services load. 3. MPC shall appropriately credit or debit the next available monthly MRA Tariff invoice for the MPC share of any OATT True-Ups. Upon the Customer Transfer Date, Customer shall no longer receive any OATT credit related to its OATT network transmission service under this Agreement, any direct assignment credits described in Article 4, or under the MRA Tariff. 4. In accordance with Article 4, Paragraph 4, MPC shall reimburse Customer on the next available monthly MRA Tariff invoice the amount charged to Customer for the costs of interconnection facilities for new Shared Service Delivery Points. 5. Customer shall utilize OATT network transmission service for load located within the Southern Companies transmission area for which it has load serving responsibilities, except for any delivery points converted to Customer Energy transmission service as described in Article 6. 6. Customer shall be responsible for requesting network transmission studies for incremental load additions associated with annual changes to the Customer Shared Service Load Percentage.
Article 12: Equipment Installation, Ownership, and Maintenance
1. MPC shall install, own, operate and maintain MPC's primary and backup metering equipment (CTs, PTs, etc.) at Shared Service Delivery Points. 2. Customer shall install, own, operate, and maintain primary communications from each Shared Service Delivery Point for purposes of data extraction and load reporting. MPC shall install secondary communications for meter diagnostic, health and power quality metrics. 3. Upon the Customer Transfer Date, Customer shall have the option to purchase all metering and communications equipment owned by MPC or Southern Company described in Paragraphs 1 and 2 at net book value. 4. Customer and MPC shall work to accommodate necessary changes between all affected balancing authorities to accurately monitor and account for Customer load served in the MPC transmission area and to accommodate Customer's service of one hundred percent (100%) of Customer's Member's load as of the Customer Transfer Date. Service to Customer's portion of Shared Service Delivery Points pursuant to the Agreement shall be provided consistent with the methods used to serve other Customer Shared Service Delivery Points.
Article 13: Miscellaneous Provisions 1. This Agreement is made pursuant to the MRA Tariff (which is a filed-rate with FERC), is subject to the prior approval of FERC, and may be changed only by mutual agreement of the Parties (also subject to the prior approval of FERC), or by order of FERC. 2. Nothing contained in this Agreement shall be construed as affecting in any way the right of either Party unilaterally to make application to the FERC for a change in rates under Section 205 or Section 206 of the Federal Power Act and pursuant to FERC's Rules and Regulations promulgated thereunder, or to oppose such an application. 3. Any changes to the rates, terms, and conditions stated herein shall be subject to FERC's just and reasonable standard of review, not the public interest standard of review. 4. This Agreement may be executed in counterparts, including by facsimile or electronic scan, all of which together shall constitute one agreement binding on all Parties hereto. 5. This Agreement constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties regarding the subject matter stated herein and supersedes all other representations or agreements. This Agreement may be amended only in writing and signed by both parties. Cooperative Energy Mississippi Power Company

?WHOLESALE ELECTRIC SERVICE TO WHOLESALE CUSTOMERS RATE SCHEDULE "MRA-31"
APPLICABILITY
This rate schedule applies to wholesale electric power service to any existing MRA tariff customer (as herein defined) for resale and/or distribution by such wholesale customer to its customers. The term "wholesale customer" shall mean any cooperative electric power association organized under the laws of the State of Mississippi for the purpose of rendering retail electric service to its customers, any cooperative electric power association organized under the laws of the State of Mississippi for the purpose of generating and transmitting electric power for sale at wholesale to distributing cooperative electric power associations, municipalities of the State of Mississippi engaged in providing retail electric service to its inhabitants and other retail customers adjacent thereto, and/or any other entity engaged in furnishing retail electric service to its customers. This rate schedule shall apply individually to service at each delivery point served hereunder. This rate schedule is part of a tariff consisting of, in addition to this schedule, terms and conditions and a service delivery point contract form.
AVAILABILITY
Service under this rate schedule is available for an initial period of not less than that specified in the Service Delivery Point Contract, from the existing 115 kV transmission lines of Company for delivery at 12, 23, 46 or 115 kV. At the option of Company, service hereunder may be available from its lines of lower voltage for delivery at the rated voltage of such lines.
MONTHLY RATE FOR SERVICE
$1,630.00 Delivery Point Charge; plus $19.70 per kW for kW required; plus $0.016406 per kWh for all kWh
DETERMINATION OF CUSTOMERS' MONTHLY KILOWATT REQUIREMENT
Customer's kilowatt requirement each month for each delivery point shall be the average kilowatts it requires from the Company during the sixty minute period coincident with the Company's monthly peak hour, as measured by a suitable meter and read to the nearest full kilowatt. Such requirement shall not be less than 50% of kilowatts contracted for when service is delivered at less than 115 kV, nor in any case less than five hundred (500) kilowatts. Whenever customer's power factor is found to be less than 85% lagging, the kilowatt requirement as determined herein may be adjusted to the equivalent of 85% lagging power factor upon ninety days advance notice.
If for the last month of service to a Delivery Point, the number of billing days is less than 25, the demand will be determined by the coincident peak, if it occurs within the usage period, or the non-coincident peak if the coincident peak does not occur within the usage period. The resulting demand will be pro-rated for the number of days of service as compared to a 30 day month.
DISCOUNT FOR SERVICE DELIVERY AT 115 KV
When Company delivers service under this rate schedule at 115,000 nominal volts and Customer furnishes, operates, and maintains the complete stepdown transformer substation necessary for it to receive such service, the above charges will be subject to a discount of $1.55 per kW as determined above. In the event Company elects to install low side metering with such equipment necessary to compensate for transformer and customer owned line losses, such discount shall be conditioned upon Customer supplying to Company the characteristics of its transformers and lines for use in determining such losses.
CREDIT FOR OATT SERVICE
If Company and Customer agree that Customer may provide a portion of the generation to any delivery points served by Company under this MRA tariff, Customer shall arrange for and thereafter take transmission services for all loads at all Customer’s MRA tariff delivery points under Southern Companies Open Access Transmission Tariff (“OATT”) and shall receive a billing credit under this MRA tariff in the amount paid by Customer for such OATT transmission services and for the required OATT ancillary services for the generation provided by Company under this MRA tariff. No such billing credit shall be provided for generation provided by Customer or for generation delivered through the Company to the Customer from the United States of America, Department of Energy, acting through the Southeastern Power Administration.
MINIMUM MONTHLY BILL
In consideration of the readiness of Company to furnish service under this rate schedule, no monthly bill will be rendered for less than the delivery point charge plus the charge per kilowatt of Customer's requirement, as determined above.
FUEL COST ADJUSTMENT CLAUSE
All bills rendered under rates subject to this schedule shall be increased by an annualized fuel cost recovery factor per kWh calculated as of each November to be applied January through December immediately following the calculation month. The factor shall include a true-up adjustment for any (over) under collection in the twelve-month period immediately preceding the calculation month (November through October).
The Company's budgeted energy costs and kWh sales for the twelve month application period will be used to develop the wholesale energy cost per kWh.
Where:
FCR = Fuel Cost Recovery Factor to be added per kWh each month for twelve months beginning with the January billing month.
BEC = Budgeted Energy Cost determined by adding projected cost of fuel at Company's generating plants (including transportation cost, and excluding fuel costs at plant on-site of specific customer, and excluding specifically assigned capacity) and projected costs of purchased energy (excluding all capacity charges) and subtracting the fuel component of the revenue projected to be derived from non-territorial energy sales.
BTS = Budgeted Total Sales determined by subtracting projected kWh to be generated on-site of specific customer from projected territorial kWh energy sales.
BWS = Budgeted Booked Wholesale Sales determined by subtracting projected retail and wholesale market-based kWh sales from BTS.
